We are wearing the new sheet steel helmet; it is heavy and inconvenient, but it gives serious protection against bursts of fusants and against ricochets, so one carries it without grumbling. We also have a lot of gear against asphyxiating gases. But we will be poorly supplied: a single meal, at night, which will usually arrive cold; and this is explained both by the length of the guts and by the difficulty of traversing a large uncovered area.

To this somewhat gloomy but true picture it is advisable to add two corrective measures; first we will have a defensive role, we are responsible for rehabilitating the very upset sector; then the Germans counter-attacked little, owing to the lack of manpower and the state of their affairs in Champagne. For these 2 reasons, it may very well be that we do not have to look them in the eye; this is also the unanimous wish here.
My letter will reach you in the midst of relocation and worry; I will try to take my part from afar; it will distract me and merge me a little more with you. I wish you calm and courage to triumph over these small difficulties.
You know how much I love you and what tender kisses I send you, share with our dear little ones.
(signed) DÃ©lÃ©age

Wednesday, September 29, 1915
My dear Louisette,
I promised you, almost solemnly, to tell you the truth; I will do it, but on the other hand you gave me the assurance that you would have strong nerves and a firm heart.
Since this morning I have been in trenches conquered for 2 days, all of these trenches and intestines form a real "labyrinth", where I wandered for 3 hours last night, absolutely lost. The traces of the ardent struggle are numerous and striking; and first of all they are more than half destroyed by the hurricane of grape shot that our artillery threw there, so they are inconvenient and horribly dirty in spite of the urgent repairs which we made there; everything is missing: water (clean or dirty), hoses, latrines; they are less than 200 meters from the 1st enemy line, with which they communicate by sealed guts; they are strewn with French and German corpses; without almost disturbing me I counted 20 frozen in the most macabre attitudes. This neighborhood is not yet foul-smelling, but it still hurts the eyes; this morning, at 5 o'clock, we arrived wet and exhausted, and I entered the first shelter to relax, I noticed a good board, lay down on it, found it soft, but 5 minutes later I noticed that she made a bedstead on 2 German corpses; well, believe me, it still does something, at least the first time. We are cooking loudly all around us and it really is sometimes a din; already I hardly greet any more.

The evil is not there; it is especially in the weather which is dreadful; for at least 3 days, gusts of rain have followed showers; the guts are unspeakable quagmires, where one slips, where one gets dreadfully muddy; so I am superlative dirty, at least to the waist; my hands are muddy and will remain so until departure; my shoes are full of water; fortunately the body is dry, for the air is almost cold and the sky livid. Around me people are making a face! We will need a lot of patience and morale.
